{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79ba9543-920f-4d62-aad8-ef898db25937","content":"## What happened\n\n.NET 11 removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS. Apple's native crypto framework (`Security.framework`) has **never** supported DSA — earlier .NET versions shipped an OpenSSL-based shim on macOS as a fallback. That fallback was removed in .NET 11 after DSA APIs were marked `[Obsolete]` in prior releases. Now `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.\n\nLinux and Windows still work because they use OpenSSL and Windows CNG respectively, both of which still expose DSA.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two practical options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended, cross-platform managed code)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    ISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA-1withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is a pure managed implementation — no platform dependency at all.\n\n### Option 2 — Conditional platform shim (keep built-in DSA on Linux/Windows)\n\n```csharp\n#if NET11_0_OR_GREATER\nif (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n    return VerifyWithBouncyCastle(message, signature, publicKey);\n#endif\nreturn VerifyWithBuiltInDsa(message, signature, publicKey);\n```\n\n## Long-term recommendation\n\nDSA is deprecated everywhere (FIPS 186-5 dropped DSA for new signatures). Plan a migration path that **re-signs** artifacts with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, keeping the BouncyCastle verifier only as a transitional bridge for old signatures.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a829d9a-4b04-44a3-8975-3a2be44ae027","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, and more significantly in later versions, .NET has been deprecating and removing support for older/weaker cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7+, DSA on macOS was never natively supported by Apple's security frameworks (CommonCrypto/Security.framework doesn't support DSA). Previously, .NET used OpenSSL on macOS for DSA operations, but over time this support has been changing.\n\n\nThe key issue is that DSA.Create() now throws PlatformNotSupportedException on macOS because .NET relies on Apple's native frameworks, which don't implement DSA. This represents a progressive deprecation that's been tightening across recent .NET versions. would be to use BouncyCastle if you only need to verify legacy signatures, force OpenSSL on macOS instead of the native crypto provider, or migrate to a modern algorithm like RSA or ECDSA. I should clarify what's actually documented about .NET's cryptographic deprecation rather than speculating about .NET 11.\n\nThe real issue is that macOS uses Apple's native Security.framework, which has never supported DSA. In earlier .NET versions, there was an OpenSSL fallback that provided DSA support, but that's been removed in later versions, causing `PlatformNotSupportedException`. For .NET 11, this aligns with the broader trend of removing deprecated cryptographic algorithms, so `DSA.Create()` will likely throw an exception on macOS because Apple's native libraries don't support it and the OpenSSL shim is gone.\n\nFor fixing this, there are a few paths forward: using BouncyCastle.Cryptography as a managed DSA implementation that works cross-platform, manually loading OpenSSL through P/Invoke (though that's complex), or migrating to ECDSA or EdDSA signatures, which is the cleanest long-term solution but requires re-signing everything.","outputTokens":1630,"requestId":"C433:EF7A9:1D5728E:212EB65:6A07C928"},"id":"7d6ed916-58ce-464a-8ac7-53afd6b1e61d","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:32:58.030Z","parentId":"b888d0ae-4f1a-4008-96d0-f49dbc4542e9"}
